[1] Case updates
- Epidemiological situation report, 5 May 2019, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://mailchi.mp/sante.gouv.cd/ebola_kivu_5mai19?e=f96cddba3b

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 4 May 2019:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 1554, of which 1488 have been confirmed and 66 are probable. In total, there were 1029 deaths (963 confirmed and 66 probable) and 438 people healed;
- 213 suspected cases under investigation;
- 9 new confirmed cases, including 3 in Katwa, 2 in Musienene, 2 in Mandima, 1 in Kalunguta, and 1 in Mabalako;
- 10 deaths of confirmed cases, including 6 community/hospital deaths -- 2 in Katwa, 2 in Mandima, and 2 in Musienene; 4 ETC/CT deaths -- 3 in Butembo and 1 in Mabalako;
- 4 new recoveries released from the Beni ETC.

News of the response
Temporary paralysis of Butembo's response activities
----------------------------------------------------
- Response activities were temporarily paralyzed in Butembo and nearby health areas on Sat 4 May 2019 following a demonstration by motorcycle taxi drivers who had placed wooden barricades on the main road arteries of Butembo town. Protesters also attacked handwashing devices throughout the city.
- The day before, Fri 3 May 2019, the teams of safe and dignified burials (EDS [in French]) of the civil protection of North Kivu were called to carry out the EDS of a woman living in Katwa recently deceased of Ebola. At the end of the EDS, an altercation would have occurred after bikers tried to attack the EDS teams and their security escort. An investigation is underway.
- To ease tensions, the ATAMOV President, the Motorcycle and Vehicle Taxi Drivers Association, and the customary chiefs had an exchange with the bikers and asked them not to hinder the work of the response teams. The response activities had partially resumed this Sun 5 May 2019. An increase in the number of cases and deaths is expected in the coming days following this temporary cessation of response activities to limit the spread of the virus in the community.

Since the start of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018, 111 579 people have been vaccinated [total numbers of people vaccinated in North Kivu, Ituri, Tshopo, and Haut-Uele provinces can be seen at the source URL above].

--
